g.text: “We're talking about immigrant detention, how immigrants get into deportation proceedings in the first place. We also know that discrimination looks differently for Black migrants in those situations, too. We [need to] understand that Black migrants are also facing a different relationship to the state than the majority of individuals who are in detention proceedings who are Latinx folks.”

“ The solution [to law enforcement] is going to be the imagination of a system of social control because we're always going to need one that looks entirely different, that is based on different assumptions, that hopefully gets at how our society is organized at the fundamental level.”

“I DO WANT TO EMPHASIZE THAT WE CAN DO BOTH OF THESE THINGS. WE CAN DEFUND, DIVEST—WHATEVER TERMS YOU WOULD LIKE TO USE—WHILE ALSO PROPOSING THE ALTERNATIVE. BUT I ALSO THINK THAT ALL OF THAT REQUIRES US TO BE DEEPLY IN COMMUNITY. ”

“ I've been quite heartened, and it's a source of optimism for me personally, by the proliferation of mutual aid, both as a concept and a practice. I think in our current moment, we have viewed it through the lens of disaster relief more than anything else, but a recalibration of that premise and that concept of strengthening community by taking care of community is absolutely crucial to moving forward.”
